The Eternal Dungeon is an instanced endless dungeon run for a solo
player or a small group.

Use:

  eternal enter [floor]
  eternal status
  eternal shop
  eternal buy <item>
  eternal leave
  eternal rejoin
  eternal leaderboard [v2|legacy]
  eternal choose <1-3>

Each run is private to its entrants. Floors are generated for the run,
with objectives, affixes, and route choices. Completing the floor
objective opens a portal to the next level.

Use portal <route> or enter portal <route> when the dungeon offers
routes such as safe, elite, boss, or unstable. Riskier routes pay more
Eternal Shards and make the next floor more dangerous.

Recover and cleanse objectives appear in earlier chambers before the
final leader. Look for the relic or shrine in the room description, then
use recover relic or cleanse shrine after its guardians are gone.

When the dungeon offers a checkpoint bargain, the run leader can use
eternal choose <1-3> before advancing.

Checkpoints unlock every 5 floors. Solo checkpoints belong to the
player who unlocked them. Group checkpoints belong to the exact party
composition that unlocked them, so the same players must reunite to use
those group checkpoints.

Use eternal enter [floor] to start from an unlocked checkpoint. Use
eternal status to view your available solo checkpoints and, when your
party is assembled, any group checkpoints for that composition.

Leaderboard entries show the starting floor when a run began from a
checkpoint. Skipped floors do not grant reward compensation. V2 and
legacy leaderboards are separate because the dungeon rules are different.

Personal leader and boss chests separate premium treasure from crafting
supply. Gilded and plain chests guarantee ember materials, repeat shard
caches retain a smaller material chance, and tier-appropriate recipe cards
are protected by a five-miss pity counter. Persistent materials and cards
are also available from eternal shop for fixed shard prices.

See also: help eternal, help eternal_dungeon
